<dl id="n53097o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097o">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097o"> 97(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the general a ghost, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097o"><li>FW 343.34 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097o">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097o">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097o">MS BL 47480-81v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:154 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097o">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">If, therefore, one strolls along the firing line&mdash;a tedious amusement at all times&mdash;it is more than likely that one will find long stretches completely deserted. The scene is desolate; the walk is strangely eerie. Walls of sandbags tower on each side, in some cases two or three feet above one&apos;s head; the clouds go scudding by, while the shadows of a traverse dance fantastically as a flare comes hissing down. The Hun is thirty yards away; the silence is absolute; the place is <mark>ghostly with the phantoms of forgotten men</mark>. <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) A point of Detail, 44</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
